I sat on the edge of my bed, phone buzzing in my hand. My sister’s text glowed on the screen: “Can we talk? I feel like you’re always taking her side.” I could hear my girlfriend in the kitchen, her voice tense as she called my name. We’d argued again last night about money—how we spend it, how we save it. She wanted to talk things through, to resolve it before it festered. But my sister needed me to listen, to be patient and not judge her choices, even when I disagreed. I felt pulled in two directions. My girlfriend expected me to step up, to fix things between us, but my sister wanted me to just be there, to accept her without trying to change her. My chest tightened as I stared at the wall, wishing I could be the brother she needed and the boyfriend she deserved, but knowing that whatever I did, someone would feel let down.

