Story:
I was getting ready to leave for the movies with my friends when my younger brother poked his head into my room. “Hey, can I come with you guys tonight?” he asked, his eyes hopeful. I remembered how Mom always said we should include each other, and I wanted him to feel like he belonged. But just as I was about to answer, my phone buzzed. It was a message from my friend, Sarah: “Hey, are we meeting at the mall or the theater? I’m confused.” She’d been upset with me last week for not communicating clearly, and I knew she expected me to be more open and responsive this time. I felt torn. If I took a minute to explain things to Sarah, my brother might feel ignored or unwanted, like I was brushing him off. But if I focused on my brother, Sarah might get frustrated again, thinking I didn’t care about her feelings or our plans. Both of them were counting on me in different ways, and I could feel the pressure building in my chest as I stood there, phone in hand, caught between being a good brother and a good friend.

